  "laps": "57",
  "distance": "308.326 km (191.584 miles)",
  "event_preview": "Miami International Autodrome measures 5.412 km (3.363 mi) and features 19 turns built around Hard Rock Stadium in Miami Gardens, Florida. Designed by Apex Circuit Design and inaugurated in 2022, it is one of the newest venues on the Formula 1 calendar and returns in 2025 as a Sprint weekend for the second consecutive year. The layout combines three long straights - offering plenty of DRS overtaking opportunities - with a technical infield section and a sweeping lakeside complex, producing a varied rhythm that challenges both high-speed stability and low-speed mechanical grip. The track surface sits on a car park and tends to be slippery early in the weekend before rubbering in significantly by qualifying, making session-to-session evolution particularly pronounced. The official race lap record stands at 1:29.708, set by Max Verstappen for Red Bull during the 2023 Miami Grand Prix, while the all-time qualifying lap record also belongs to Verstappen - a 1:26.814 clocked in Q2 of that same weekend, when he DNF'd in Q3 and failed to set a representative pole lap.",
  "tyre_compounds": "Tyre supplier Pirelli brought the C3, C4, and C5 tyre compounds.",
